'''Imcandoria''' was the former city of the [[Imcando dwarves]], located somewhere in the far north,{{CiteNPC|npc=Ghost (Ruins of Camdozaal)|quote=Rumour has it [the Imcando] once lived in a great city in the far north.}} presumably in the same region as [[Acheron]]. The region around Imcandoria was also home to a group of unspecified [[giant]]s who were metalworkers, as well as several [[Auspah]] tribes; in addition, they are known to have traded with [[Fremennik]] tribes.{{CiteNPC|npc=Freja|quote=I had found a lot of trade scrolls with early Fremennik tribes on the isle [of Garmr] too...}}

==History==
Towards the end of the [[Second Age]], an Imcando acolyte had discovered a strange black idol with odd scratched markings along the beach of the [[Isle of Garmr]]. Presuming it to be a runic relic of the [[Fremennik]] tribes,{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=One of the acolytes discovered a strange idol along the beach today, it has the oddest markings scratched upon it, much akin to the runic rocks of the Fremennik.}} the idol was sent to the Elders of Imcandoria for safekeeping.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=The Elders of Imcandoria will know what to do with such a relic so the other Seers and I have agreed that it will be sent to them immediately.}}

Two months after the idol was sent away, storms around Imcandoria began to grow more and more ferocious, so much that the dwarves were forced to seek refuge in the Forge of Giants in the lower Necropolis{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=It has been two moons since we sent the idol away and the storms have turned increasingly ferocious. We have gone below into the lower Necropolis, hoping to seek refuge in the Forge of Giants.}} (which is presumed to be a large cemetery from the definition of the word). Though the giants allowed them to stay, food supplies began to run low.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=The giants allowed us to stay in their domain. However, our time here is limited by our food stores, for no edible food can be produced in these horrible depths.}}

Three months after taking refuge in the Forge of Giants, a plan to journey into Imcandoria was planned;{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=In three moons we will return to the surface and attempt the journey into Imcandoria.}} having seen omens of death in their forges, the giants suggested journeying to Imcandoria with reinforcements, and had given the Imcando a fiery jewel to bargain with the {{RSL|Auspah}} tribes that live around the city.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=The giants have seen omens of death in the forges and have suggested we go with reinforcements. They've given us a bright fiery jewel that we can use to bargain with the Auspah tribes around Imcandoria.}}

With five months having gone by since the idol had been found, the Imcando that had journeyed into the city had found it empty,{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=The city is empty, there are sounds coming from the temple. We approach with caution.}} only to discover piles of bodies and pools of blood in the temple. Here, a grotesque mass with three boulbous eyes and clawed tentacles, believed to be indicative of {{RSL|Xau-Tak}}'s presence, had settled in.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=Piles of bodies. Pools of blood. A large globulous mass sat hungrily on a throne of oily black rock, a shock of tentacles capped with claws dangled above its three pulsing bulbous eyes.}} The Elders of Imcandoria, entirely in blood and thick sludge, have been entirely corrupted by the globulous mass, chanting incantations in an unknown language.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=The Elders circled the creature, chanting incantations in a strange unknown tongue, covered head to toe in a mixture of blood and thick black sludge.}}

The grotesque creature, having noticed the Imcando's presence, soon attacked, with the Elders following suit, causing the temple to go up in flames.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=[The elders] paid us no attention until the creature noticed our presence and began screaming. A fight soon broke out and the temple quickly turned into a blaze, the flames licking the ceiling.}} The Elders, cackling as they were being burned alive, presumably perished.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=The harsh cackle from the elders as they burned, pierced our minds with unimaginable terror. We're none the wiser of how that... thing... came to be, but that idol must have been far older than we first assumed.}}

With their numbers dwindled and the storm quietening, the group returned to the Isle of Garmr. With the city fallen and the lands turned frozen, the Imcando dwarves were forced to leave their home. Before leaving, Gulbrand, the Highseer of the Isle of Garmr, documented the events he beared witness to in a heavy tome inscribed on rock paper,{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=I, Highseer Gulbrand of the Isle of Garmr, have assembled various entries detailing the fall of Imcandoria.}}{{CiteNPC|npc=Freja|quote=These texts are inscribed in rock paper in a tome even I struggle to lift.}} and placed it by the entrance hall in the Necropolis, to serve as a warning not to travel back to Imcandoria.{{CiteNPC|npc=Imcandoria's fall|quote=I leave this tome in the entrance hall of our great Necropolis. Heed my warning reader and do not travel into that frozen wasteland. All that awaits is death.}}

With no home to return to, the remaining Imcando dwarves were promised a new home by [[Saradomin]],{{CiteNPC|npc=Ghost (Ruins of Camdozaal)|quote=It seems [the Imcando] have been promised a new home here in return for wiping us out.}} who would have his forces lay siege to [[Lassar]] and grant the Imcando dwarves a new settlement in the ruins of the [[Zaros]]ian fortress.

Led by [[Yonrith Lovakengj]], the Saradominist forces marched upon Lassar and destroyed it in one of many attacks on the [[Zarosian Empire]] that began after the [[Betrayal of Zaros]]. Once the Zarosian forces have been driven out, the Imcando dwarves set to build their new city, naming it [[Camdozaal]].

